{
  "stem": "7458.1",
  "chunk_idx": 9,
  "model": "openai/gpt-oss-120b",
  "elapsed_s": 3.4,
  "sentences_input": [
    {
      "segment_idx": 33,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 6,
      "text": "We had no delinquency, no divorce, no-- not many suicides.",
      "word_count": 10
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 33,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 7,
      "text": "Life was very calm.",
      "word_count": 4
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 33,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 8,
      "text": "Most people were born, lived all their lives, and died in the same town.",
      "word_count": 14
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 33,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 9,
      "text": "In fact, I have an article, here, on my desk in Yiddish that shows that Jews settled in Jasionovka in 1731.",
      "word_count": 21
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 33,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 10,
      "text": "And I have no reason to doubt that some of my own family were the first settlers, because whenever I would ask my father or my grandfather, Grandpa, where did you come from, he would say, Jasionovka.",
      "word_count": 37
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 33,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 11,
      "text": "And so, since my father was born sometimes in the 19th century, and my grandfather probably early part of the 19th century, I have no reason to think that they were not settlers in Jasionovka as early as 1731.",
      "word_count": 39
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 34,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 0,
      "text": "Yes.",
      "word_count": 1
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 34,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 1,
      "text": "Now, The best way to describe the existence of Jewish people in the small towns was it was like a-- an island of serenity in a sea of hostility.",
      "word_count": 29
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 34,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 2,
      "text": "Although the town itself was serene and in many ways a happy place to grow up and to live, poverty and hard work notwithstanding, we were surrounded by Poles who refused to let us become part of their society-- part of their surroundings.",
      "word_count": 43
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 34,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 3,
      "text": "Therefore, many Jewish people in the town never even learned to speak Polish, because there was so little interaction between the Poles and the Jews.",
      "word_count": 25
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 34,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 4,
      "text": "There was only a few occasions when Poles and Jews would be together.",
      "word_count": 13
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 34,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 5,
      "text": "One of them, which occurred several times a year, was a market day.",
      "word_count": 13
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 34,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 6,
      "text": "In Yiddish it was called yarid.",
      "word_count": 6
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 34,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 7,
      "text": "In fact, that was a very major event in the life of the shtetl, because in the shtetl there were many shoemakers, tailors, leather producers, candle-makers, and so on and so forth.",
      "word_count": 32
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 34,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 8,
      "text": "They would produce things that the farmers and the Poles needed.",
      "word_count": 11
    }
  ],
